questions.question:
The height of a tree is defined as the number of edges on the longest path in the tree. The function shown in the pseudo-code below is invoked as height(root) to compute the height of a binary tree rooted at the tree pointer root.

int height(treeptr n) {
  if (n == NULL) return -1;
  if (n->left == NULL && n->right == NULL) return 0;
  else {
    h1 = height(n->left);
    h2 = height(n->right);
    return B1;
  }
}

The appropriate expression for the two boxes B1 and B2 are:

A. B1: (1 + height(n->right)), B2: (1 + max(h1, h2))
B. B1: (1 + max(h1, h2)), B2: (1 + max(h1, h2))
C. B1: (1 + height(n->right)), B2: max(h1, h2)
D. B1: (1 + height(n->right)), B2: max(h1, h2)
